05564nam a22007935i 9789048557172DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a9789048557172  a(DE-B1597)624304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0271302bisacsh00aBeyond the Pale :bDutch Extreme Violence in the Indonesian War of Independence, 1945-1949. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (592 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOnafhankelijkheid, Dekolonisatie, Geweld en Oorlog in Indonesië 1945-195000tFrontmatter -- tMaps -- tContent -- tI. Introduction -- tII. Intermezzo -- tIII. Research Results -- tIV. Closing Remarks -- tV. Epilogue -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tFurther reading -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the authors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIndonesia declared its independence on 17 August 1945, two days after the Japanese capitulation that marked the end of World War II in Asia. Refusing to recognize Indonesian independence, the Netherlands attempted to gain control over the decolonization process by force, leading to four years of arduous negotiations and bitter warfare. In 2005, the Dutch government declared that the Netherlands had been 'on the wrong side of history' and should not have engaged in this war. However, to this day, the government maintains its position from 1969 about violence at the hands of Dutch soldiers during this war: Yes, there had been 'excesses', but as a rule, the armed forces had behaved 'correctly'. In recent years, this official position has increasingly, and more loudly, been called into question. In Beyond the Pale, conclusions of ten separate studies are presented from different perspectives, addressing the extent to which the Dutch armed forces used extreme violence on a structural basis and offering an assessment of their actions. The authors also examine how the Dutch government and society dealt with this extreme violence both during and after the war. Was it discussed, was it punished or covered up, and what developments does this reflect?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4a20th century, c 1900 to c 1999. 4aAUP Algemeen. 4aAsian history. 4aColonial Studies. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary History. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aIndonesia. 4aMilitary history: post-WW2 conflicts. 4aNational liberation and independence. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  aIndonesia, decolonisation, independence, violence, war.1 aBrocades Zaalberg, Thijs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchheim, Eveline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaptain, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEickhoff, Martijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarid, Hilmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrakking, Roel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarmanny, Azarja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaaij, Meindert van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemperman, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLimpach, Rémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuttikhuis, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re